text.Taxonomy and naming:
Verticordia roei was first formally described by Stephan Endlicher in 1838 and the description was published in Stirpium Australasicarum Herbarii Hugeliani Decades Tres. The type specimen was collected by John Septimus Roe. The specific epithet (roei) honours Roe, the first surveyor-general of Western Australia.Alex George undertook a review of the genus Verticordia in 1991 and described two subspecies:
Verticordia roei Endl.  subsp. roei which has stamens 3–4 mm (0.1–0.2 in) long and styles 2–3 mm (0.08–0.1 in) long;
Verticordia roei subsp. meiogona  A.S.George  which has stamens 1.5–2.5 mm (0.06–0.1 in) long and styles 1.5–2.0 mm (0.06–0.08 in) long.George placed this species in subgenus Verticordia, section Catocalypta along with V. inclusa, V. apecta, V. insignis, V. habrantha, V. lehmannii and V. pritzelii.
